        bodyEn: '''Zeus ruled from the summit of Olympus, holding the thunderbolt as a symbol of authority and enforcer of justice. He became father of gods and men, guardian of oaths and guests. Poseidon built a splendid palace on the sea floor, riding a chariot drawn by bronze-hooved horses; his wrath stirred the storms and earthquakes feared by sailors. Hades ruled the subterranean kingdom among the souls, ensuring none escaped death; his helm of darkness made him invisible. Though their realms were separate, the three often interacted. Poseidon occasionally challenged Zeus\'s authority, while Hades rarely left his kingdom except on great occasions. This division affirmed that cosmic power was collective, not singular as it had been under Cronus.''',
